    problem: 'The outer loop had three deadlock modes that made one stuck item block the entire repair backlog forever. (1) Scope-gate skips left repair_status=pending, so the same item was re-picked run-after-run — an item touching a Restricted-tier file would never advance. (2) attempt_count only incremented on test/commit failures, so any failure earlier in the protocol (investigation, AUP rejection, URL fetch) never incremented and the attempt_count>=3 freeze never fired. One item could be investigated and abandoned daily forever without ever hitting the freeze. (3) Silent git push failures on detached HEAD were never verified, so rollback commits were created locally and lost on process exit while the outer loop thought the rollback had landed. The Data Science Salon incident surfaced all three at once: AUP rejection during investigation, queue-head poisoning blocked the backlog behind it, and the oscillation freeze never triggered because attempt_count stayed at 1.',
    action: 'Four protocol fixes plus one database state addition. (1) New repair_status value "proposed" — the human-review queue. When the outer loop investigates an item but cannot act on it autonomously (Restricted/Never tier or out-of-scope fix), it transitions the item to "proposed" and logs the proposal to repair_log. Proposed items are filtered out of the selection query, so they stop blocking the backlog. (2) New last_terminal_failure_at column — any protocol step that terminates (success, failure, skip, proposal) writes this timestamp. The selection query filters out items touched in the last 24h, preventing same-day retry loops on structurally stuck items. (3) attempt_count increments on ANY terminal failure, not just test/commit. Investigation failures, AUP rejections, URL fetch failures, scope-gate skips, and push failures all count. This makes the attempt_count>=3 freeze protect the whole protocol, not just the fix stage. (4) Push verification is mandatory — silent push failures are fatal, not "next run will fix it." If git push fails for any reason, the outer loop transitions to failed and logs the push failure reason to repair_log. (5) Oscillation freeze query updated to catch any pending/failed item with attempt_count>=3, not just items where repair_status=failed specifically.',
    result: 'The outer loop can no longer deadlock on a single item. Scope-gated items transition to the human-review queue and stop being re-selected. Investigation-phase failures count toward the freeze, so AUP-rejected items eventually get frozen instead of being retried forever. The 24h cooldown prevents same-run retry loops. Push failures are caught instead of silently swept under "next run." The monitor now surfaces the proposed-items queue visibly so the user can see what the outer loop has diagnosed but can\'t touch. Foundation for Phase 1 (monitor-as-planner) which will take over strategic decisions the outer loop is wrongly trying to handle autonomously.',
